  It=E2=80=99s important to note that the sort of acquisitions the FTC is l=
ooking at almost certainly fall predominantly in this third group. Acquihir=
es of failed startups is arguably the most tangible way that big tech compa=
nies contribute to Silicon Valley=E2=80=99s durable startup culture: there =
is more reason for entrepreneurs, early employees, and investors to take a =
chance on new ideas because the big tech companies provide a backstop.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,sans=
-serif;margin-top:15px;margin-bottom:15px;padding-top:0px;padding-bottom:0p=
x;line-height:130%">  Another way to consider these benefits, meanwhile, is=
 to think about a world where acquisitions by large tech companies are seve=
rely constricted or banned:</p>
<ul style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,san=
s-serif;line-height:130%">
<li style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,san=
s-serif;line-height:130%">New technology would be diffused far more slowly =
(as the new startup scales), if at all (if the startup goes out of business=
).</li>
<li style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,san=
s-serif;line-height:130%">The amount of investment in risky technologies wi=
thout obvious avenues to go-to-market would decrease, simply because it wou=
ld be far less likely that investors would earn a return even if the techno=
logy worked.</li>
<li style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,san=
s-serif;line-height:130%">The risk of working for a startup would increase =
significantly, both because the startup would be less likely to succeed and=
 also because the failure scenario is unemployment.</li>
</ul>
