color:rgb(250,166,52)" target=3D"_blank">There are structural reasons</a> w=
hy Big Tech looks poised to dominate AI, including the importance of cloud =
infrastructure, data, and existing distribution channels. It=E2=80=99s nota=
ble, though, that a huge amount of the investment into AI startups, particu=
larly the ambitious ones actually building models, is also coming from Big =
Tech: they can de-risk those investments by providing credits instead of do=
llars as Microsoft has, or by double-dipping on GPU sales like Nvidia is. T=
raditional investors, meanwhile, don=E2=80=99t have a clear exit if acquisi=
tions are off the table.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,sans=
-serif;margin-top:15px;margin-bottom:15px;padding-top:0px;padding-bottom:0p=
x;line-height:130%">Big Tech, though, is making it work anyways: Microsoft =
is definitely getting the Inflection team and model, and maybe also the GPU=
s. Meanwhile, the one traditional venture firm on Inflection=E2=80=99s cap =
table was Greylock, where Reid Hoffman, the only Inflection co-founder not =
going to work at Microsoft, is partner. Hoffman, of course, doesn=E2=80=99t=
 need to go to Microsoft because he, conveniently enough, is already on the=
 behemoth=E2=80=99s board, which means he was perfectly placed to engineer =
a scenario where Greylock and the other investors are poised to get their m=
oney back for a failed startup.</p>
<p style=3D"font-size:17px;font-weight:300;font-family:Helvetica,Arial,sans=
